      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn the previous texts, we introduced the concept of equality. Logically, when something is not equal, it is automatically considered different. However, merely stating that something is different does not provide details about the extent of those differences. Therefore, it becomes necessary to quantify the differences between objects.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_numbers",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>Numerical Relationship</h3><p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgMeter\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/Meter.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMeter', '0%')\" /><b>Figure 1</b>: Representation of a centesimal scale.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Observing Figure 1, we can note that the numbers studied previously are arranged in sequence. When a number is positioned after another, we say it is a **greater** number. Mathematically, we use the symbol (>) to express this relationship. For example: *21 > 20*",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c47a586f-6053-4b8e-8f9b-828cd6220110",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Similarly, when a number appears before another, we say it is **smaller**. To represent this, we use the symbol (<). For example: *20 < 21*",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4e3c3945-0bf4-4040-9735-546541b27a50",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "It is important to highlight that the opening of the comparison symbol, whether greater (>) or less (<), always points towards the larger number.\n\nAnother important point is that when working with significantly larger numbers, we use the symbol (&#8811;). Similarly, for significantly smaller numbers, we use the symbol (&#8810;)",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c47a586f-6053-4b8e-8f9b-828cd6220110",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4e3c3945-0bf4-4040-9735-546541b27a50",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><h4>Practice</h4>When we establish a mathematical inequality, it’s essential to remember that once defined, it must remain consistent. In other words, if we change one side of the equation, we must make a corresponding change to the other side to maintain balance. Let's do a simple exercise with numbers and our hands, using arrows to illustrate:</p><p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Equação</i></th><th>Mão esquerda</th><th>Mão direita</th><th>Setas</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\" id=\"leftnum\">0</span></td></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\">&lt;</span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\" id=\"rightnum\">1</span></td><td id=\"tc5f1\" style=\"background-color:white;\"><img id=\"leftHandImg\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Left_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc6f1\"><img id=\"rightHandImg\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/1Right_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc7f1\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\"style=\"font-size:4em;color:#00f;\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\">Tabela 1: Mantendo a desigualdade.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_bulding",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The Smaller as a Basis\n\nNature began by constructing small structures known as elementary particles, such as electrons. Over time, these particles grouped together to form atoms, which subsequently combined to create molecules. These molecules, in turn, interacted and assembled into increasingly complex structures. This gradual process led to the emergence of the first living beings, which underwent billions of years of evolution, resulting in the remarkable diversity of species we know today, including our own",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "6dfe4b3b-8338-46ab-8149-2e073414907e",
                     "text": "<i>NASA</i>",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "34a775e9-d5b7-4bed-b5cd-28f77fc1aa65",
                     "text": "Moody, E.R.R., Álvarez-Carretero, S., Mahendrarajah, T.A. <i>et al</i>",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "27ff155c-c38d-4619-a435-4d95fd55071d",
                     "text": "Pirula",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
