      {
         "id": "SECTION_limits",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Limits\n\nThe concepts of \"greater\" and \"less\" are essential for defining limits. In our previous discussion, we examined how limits relate to maximum and minimum values. Additionally, we explored how limits can also be interpreted as an approximation of a specific value. In this text, we delve further into how \"greater\" and \"less\" can be applied to define limits",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Limites",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"><circle cx=\"135\" cy=\"75\" r=\"70\"></circle> <line x1=\"140\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"205\" y2=\"75\" stroke=\"black\" /> <text x=\"135\" y=\"85\">O</text>  <text x=\"175\" y=\"85\">r</text> </svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 5</b>: Círcle with radius 75.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Upper Limit\n\nAn upper limit represents the largest possible value within a given context. For example, in **Figure 5**,  we observe a circle with a radius (the distance from the center to the circumference) of 75. Since the circle is a closed geometric shape, the maximum allowable value for the radius can be mathematically expressed as *r < 75*",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e58ad730-899f-49b6-aaf8-53cb39c31f0e",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Lower Limit\n\nSimilarly, a lower limit corresponds to the smallest permissible value. Returning to **Figure 5**, consider the radius measured from the circumference toward the center. For the radius to exist, it must have a value greater than zero. Thus, the smallest allowable value for the radius can be expressed mathematically as *r > 0*",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "61b6b478-d49a-40ec-a68d-52767ebbb6cc",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Biological Limits\n\nLimits also play a crucial role in biology. For example, Alan R. Templeton’s research established clear criteria for identifying genetic boundaries within populations. To avoid classifying populations as distinct races, genetic differences (*d*) must fall between a minimum value of 0 and a maximum of 25, expressed mathematically as *0 < d < 25*",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "723b0735-b8c4-4b02-8ce6-6da033ca2454",
                     "text": "Templeton A. R.",
                     "page": "pp. 7 - 8",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "723b0735-b8c4-4b02-8ce6-6da033ca2454",
                     "text": "Templeton A. R.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Templeton also highlighted that genetic variation among humans is less than *5*, a value well within the proposed range (*0 < 5 < 25*)",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "723b0735-b8c4-4b02-8ce6-6da033ca2454",
                     "text": "Templeton A. R.",
                     "page": "pp. 7 - 8",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "723b0735-b8c4-4b02-8ce6-6da033ca2454",
                     "text": "Templeton A. R.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conclusion\n\nIn this text, we analyzed how the concepts of \"greater\" and \"less\" can be used to establish inequalities. Furthermore, we demonstrated that these concepts have broader applications, allowing for a deeper understanding of the limits discussed in the previous chapter",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
